WEBVTT

00:02.461 --> 00:05.464
[flame crackling]

00:05.464 --> 00:07.883
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:07.883 --> 00:09.968
<i>- Tonight,</i>
<i>it's the final round</i>

00:09.968 --> 00:12.095
<i>of the first ever</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire"</i>

00:12.095 --> 00:14.014
<i>Invitational Tournament.</i>

00:14.014 --> 00:16.016
<i>Over the last four weeks,</i>

00:16.016 --> 00:19.144
<i>metalsmiths from four renowned</i>
<i>classes of blade-making</i>

00:19.144 --> 00:22.272
<i>have put their skills</i>
<i>to the test</i>

00:22.272 --> 00:24.066
<i>for the right to represent</i>
<i>their class</i>

00:24.066 --> 00:26.109
<i>in this finale.</i>

00:26.109 --> 00:30.572
<i>Right now, our winning</i>
<i>farrier, armorer, blacksmith,</i>

00:30.572 --> 00:31.865
<i>and modern metalworker</i>
<i>face off...</i>

00:31.865 --> 00:33.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:33.534 --> 00:35.410
<i>In our toughest competition</i>
<i>to date.</i>

00:35.410 --> 00:38.330
This is the longest blade
that we have ever forged

00:38.330 --> 00:40.457
in round-one history.

00:40.457 --> 00:42.668
<i>Guts and glory aren't</i>
<i>the only thing at stake</i>

00:42.668 --> 00:44.753
<i>as we turn up the heat</i>

00:44.753 --> 00:46.922
<i>for our biggest</i>
<i>cash prize ever:</i>

00:46.922 --> 00:48.757
$50,000.

00:48.757 --> 00:50.425
<i>Which smith has the skill</i>

00:50.425 --> 00:52.552
<i>to take home the title</i>
<i>for their trade</i>

00:52.552 --> 00:55.681
<i>and be named "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>Tournament Champion?</i>

00:55.681 --> 00:56.807
<i>[music intensifies]</i>

00:56.807 --> 00:59.017
[metal clanking]

00:59.017 --> 01:02.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:02.354 --> 01:04.356
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:04.356 --> 01:06.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:06.483 --> 01:08.235
<i>- My name is Kirk Adkins.</i>

01:08.235 --> 01:09.820
I am a "Forged in Fire"
champion

01:09.820 --> 01:11.363
and I'm here to represent
the farriers.

01:11.363 --> 01:12.739
<i>As a farrier,</i>

01:12.739 --> 01:14.449
<i>speed and accuracy is a huge,</i>

01:14.449 --> 01:16.493
<i>important skill that you need</i>

01:16.493 --> 01:17.995
in shoeing horses, because

01:17.995 --> 01:19.371
they don't want to stand around

01:19.371 --> 01:21.206
while you kind of
figure things out.

01:21.206 --> 01:22.791
<i>- I'm Nicholas Cochiolo,</i>

01:22.791 --> 01:24.918
and I am here to represent
the armorers.

01:24.918 --> 01:26.086
<i>Armorers have to be a tailor.</i>

01:26.086 --> 01:28.255
<i>You have to be a metalsmith.</i>

01:28.255 --> 01:30.382
<i>Making something actually</i>
<i>fit someone, that's difficult.</i>

01:30.382 --> 01:32.593
<i>For me,</i>
<i>knives are pretty easy,</i>

01:32.593 --> 01:35.721
so I'm here to win it all.

01:35.721 --> 01:37.055
<i>- I'm Derick Kemper,</i>

01:37.055 --> 01:38.640
<i>the "Forged in Fire" champion</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:40.475
<i>from the blacksmith class.</i>

01:40.475 --> 01:42.019
I'm here to win the
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:42.019 --> 01:43.603
of all the classes.

01:43.603 --> 01:45.605
<i>I'm also here</i>
<i>to win $50,000</i>

01:45.605 --> 01:48.942
and the ability to completely
pay for my wedding.

01:48.942 --> 01:51.528
[laughing]

01:51.528 --> 01:53.238
- My name is Dave Parthemore,

01:53.238 --> 01:55.741
and I'm here representing
the modern metalworkers.

01:55.741 --> 01:57.409
<i>My definition of a metalworker</i>

01:57.409 --> 01:59.661
is someone that can do it all.

01:59.661 --> 02:01.705
Within these classes of smiths,

02:01.705 --> 02:03.457
my concern is with myself,

02:03.457 --> 02:05.625
because I'm the only one
I have control over.

02:05.625 --> 02:07.794
<i>[rock guitar chord]</i>

02:07.794 --> 02:09.046
- Champions.

02:09.046 --> 02:10.756
Welcome back to The Forge.

02:10.756 --> 02:12.799
Not only are you competing

02:12.799 --> 02:14.676
for the title of
tournament champion,

02:14.676 --> 02:17.262
but also, you're trying to earn

02:17.262 --> 02:21.141
the largest cash prize
in "Forged in Fire" history:

02:21.141 --> 02:23.518
$50,000,

02:23.518 --> 02:25.854
in front of a global audience

02:25.854 --> 02:28.523
and under the keen observation
of our panel of expert judges.

02:28.523 --> 02:30.275
Let's meet them now.

02:30.275 --> 02:31.902
Up first, two-time
"Forged in Fire" champion,

02:31.902 --> 02:33.695
Ben Abbott.

02:33.695 --> 02:36.073
Next, historic weapons
re-creation specialist,

02:36.073 --> 02:37.532
David Baker.

02:37.532 --> 02:39.242
And last,
edged weapons specialist

02:39.242 --> 02:41.620
Doug Marcaida.

02:41.620 --> 02:43.830
Champions, in this competition

02:43.830 --> 02:47.084
you need to be
a master weaponsmith.

02:47.084 --> 02:48.543
So with that in mind,

02:48.543 --> 02:51.505
we've chosen
a very special weapon.

02:51.505 --> 02:53.548
This is the longest blade

02:53.548 --> 02:54.716
that we have ever forged

02:54.716 --> 02:56.760
in round-one history.

02:56.760 --> 02:58.595
That weapon is...

02:58.595 --> 03:00.639
<i>[dramatic music swells]</i>

03:00.639 --> 03:02.391
<i>[musical sting]</i>

03:02.391 --> 03:04.976
The wakizashi.

03:04.976 --> 03:07.104
<i>A wakizashi is a traditional</i>
<i>Japanese blade</i>

03:07.104 --> 03:08.855
<i>shorter than a katana.</i>

03:08.855 --> 03:11.024
<i>Although the katana saw more</i>
<i>battle time,</i>

03:11.024 --> 03:14.403
<i>the wakizashi's smaller size</i>
<i>allowed the weapon to be</i>

03:14.403 --> 03:16.238
<i>an effective sidearm</i>
<i>for samurais,</i>

03:16.238 --> 03:18.365
<i>who often carried the blade</i>
<i>with them at all times.</i>

03:18.365 --> 03:20.450
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:20.450 --> 03:22.202
<i>- We're not making a knife.</i>
<i>We're making a sword.</i>

03:22.202 --> 03:23.745
<i>A wakizashi is a sword.</i>

03:23.745 --> 03:25.455
It's a challenge for me
as a champion,

03:25.455 --> 03:27.874
and I know it's a challenge
for my competitors.

03:27.874 --> 03:29.376
- Gentlemen,
you will be provided

03:29.376 --> 03:31.044
with stacks of 1095,

03:31.044 --> 03:34.005
15N20, and a brass habaki.

03:34.005 --> 03:37.092
Your blades must fall within
the following parameters.

03:37.092 --> 03:38.593
<i>The length of your blade</i>
<i>must be</i>

03:38.593 --> 03:40.762
<i>between 16 and 20 inches.</i>

03:40.762 --> 03:42.055
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of this blade</i>

03:42.055 --> 03:44.349
<i>must not exceed 28 inches.</i>

03:44.349 --> 03:46.935
- But to go from
a bunch of little pieces

03:46.935 --> 03:48.770
to a billet to a sword

03:48.770 --> 03:50.397
<i>in three hours?</i>

03:50.397 --> 03:52.858
That's bananas.

03:52.858 --> 03:54.359
- Keep in mind that
in round two,

03:54.359 --> 03:56.153
you'll attach handles
to those blades,

03:56.153 --> 03:59.531
turning them into fully
functional samurai weapons

03:59.531 --> 04:01.825
that will be tested for
strength and durability

04:01.825 --> 04:04.953
in a Wing Chun
bamboo dummy chop

04:04.953 --> 04:06.329
and for edge retention

04:06.329 --> 04:09.124
in a 3-foot pork loin slice.

04:09.124 --> 04:10.750
Good luck, gentlemen.

04:10.750 --> 04:12.669
Your three hours starts...now.

04:12.669 --> 04:14.337
<i>[intense techno music]</i>

04:14.337 --> 04:16.840
We have a real class war
going on out there

04:16.840 --> 04:20.218
between farriers, blacksmiths,
modern metalworkers,

04:20.218 --> 04:21.553
and armorers.

04:21.553 --> 04:23.305
It's gonna be
really interesting

04:23.305 --> 04:26.391
to see how each of these
different classes

04:26.391 --> 04:28.185
attacks this challenge.

04:28.185 --> 04:31.646
<i>- The materials are</i>
<i>blanks of 1095</i>

04:31.646 --> 04:34.065
<i>and 15N20.</i>

04:34.065 --> 04:36.777
<i>And what we're going to do</i>
<i>is combine them,</i>

04:36.777 --> 04:38.570
making a Damascus blade

04:38.570 --> 04:41.031
showing off
the different layers.

04:41.031 --> 04:44.242
<i>From the very beginning,</i>
<i>you have to have clean steel,</i>

04:44.242 --> 04:46.620
you have to have good fit-up,

04:46.620 --> 04:48.705
<i>and you have to have</i>
<i>proper heat.</i>

04:48.705 --> 04:50.582
<i>And then you have to have</i>
<i>the proper amount of pressure.</i>

04:50.582 --> 04:53.794
<i>These things are needed</i>
<i>to make a good weld.</i>

04:53.794 --> 04:56.505
Any one of these things
missing--it's gonna fail.

04:56.505 --> 04:58.465
<i>[rock guitar chord]</i>

04:58.465 --> 05:01.134
<i>- When I'm doing any kind</i>
<i>of Japanese sword,</i>

05:01.134 --> 05:03.303
I set an entire day

05:03.303 --> 05:05.388
just for the forging.

05:05.388 --> 05:07.349
How am I gonna make this work?
Gotta make it work.

05:07.349 --> 05:08.642
You got three hours.
Let's do this.

05:08.642 --> 05:10.393
- You have to be smart

05:10.393 --> 05:12.437
in how big of a billet
you want to start with.

05:12.437 --> 05:14.147
'Cause if you start with
a bigger billet,

05:14.147 --> 05:15.607
you get more layers,

05:15.607 --> 05:17.150
and that's fun
for the Damascus,

05:17.150 --> 05:19.361
but it just takes so much
time to draw it out.

05:19.361 --> 05:21.822
<i>- I don't need the amount</i>
<i>of material I'm using,</i>

05:21.822 --> 05:22.989
<i>but it's always better</i>
<i>to have it</i>

05:22.989 --> 05:24.324
and not need it

05:24.324 --> 05:25.951
than to need it
and not have it.

05:25.951 --> 05:27.244
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:27.244 --> 05:30.247
- Wakizashi?
That's hard.

05:30.247 --> 05:32.040
<i>I am not confident at all.</i>

05:32.040 --> 05:34.125
It's really hard to only
be able to devote

05:34.125 --> 05:36.211
<i>a little bit of time</i>
<i>to each task.</i>

05:36.211 --> 05:38.296
I'm not sure
I can pull this off.

05:38.296 --> 05:40.257
- They have to make
the longest weapon

05:40.257 --> 05:42.008
we've ever asked for

05:42.008 --> 05:44.302
in a round-one competition.

05:44.302 --> 05:45.846
It's a lot of blade to warp.

05:45.846 --> 05:47.514
It's a lot of blade to twist.

05:47.514 --> 05:49.140
It's a lot of blade to have

05:49.140 --> 05:51.017
delaminations in,

05:51.017 --> 05:52.602
especially with these layers.

05:52.602 --> 05:53.728
<i>- So I really want</i>
<i>to make sure</i>

05:53.728 --> 05:55.188
<i>I have enough steel.</i>

05:55.188 --> 05:56.857
<i>So I'm gonna use</i>
<i>all of the metal</i>

05:56.857 --> 05:58.942
and I'm gonna draw out
a big-ass billet

05:58.942 --> 06:00.360
and cut it to what I need.

06:00.360 --> 06:02.404
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:02.404 --> 06:04.573
<i>- I'm concerned about</i>
<i>the stack of steel.</i>

06:04.573 --> 06:06.950
<i>It can look very hot</i>
<i>on the outside,</i>

06:06.950 --> 06:10.078
but the inner part might not
be at welding temperature.

06:10.078 --> 06:11.997
<i>So I determined</i>
<i>that I would like</i>

06:11.997 --> 06:14.124
<i>to make two stacks</i>
<i>out of this</i>

06:14.124 --> 06:15.625
so that I know that the heat

06:15.625 --> 06:16.793
will get to the middle.

06:16.793 --> 06:18.461
- It looks like Kirk plans on

06:18.461 --> 06:20.839
forging both
of those billets out

06:20.839 --> 06:22.716
and then forge-welding
them together.

06:22.716 --> 06:24.426
<i>- The pros of the plan is</i>

06:24.426 --> 06:26.386
a smaller billet
is easier to manage,

06:26.386 --> 06:28.221
and the con is

06:28.221 --> 06:29.639
<i>I'm gonna have to spend</i>
<i>quite a bit of time</i>

06:29.639 --> 06:30.974
cleaning those up to make sure

06:30.974 --> 06:34.227
that I get a good, solid weld.

06:34.227 --> 06:35.562
<i>I've never made</i>
<i>a wakizashi before,</i>

06:35.562 --> 06:36.897
but I'm a farrier.

06:36.897 --> 06:37.898
Show me how it's
supposed to look,

06:37.898 --> 06:39.608
<i>and I'll make it.</i>

06:39.608 --> 06:40.817
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:40.817 --> 06:42.152
<i>- This is very challenging</i>

06:42.152 --> 06:44.112
<i>because of its simplicity.</i>

06:44.112 --> 06:45.822
You have pristine material.

06:45.822 --> 06:47.449
You have perfect conditions.

06:47.449 --> 06:49.367
<i>If anything fails,</i>

06:49.367 --> 06:50.994
it's on you totally.

06:50.994 --> 06:53.705
<i>But it's not magic.</i>
<i>It's a shape.</i>

06:53.705 --> 06:55.915
Metalworkers make shapes
all the time.

06:55.915 --> 06:59.169
<i>However, I have never made</i>
<i>a Japanese weapon like this,</i>

06:59.169 --> 07:00.962
ever...

07:00.962 --> 07:02.130
<i>and I'm nervous.</i>

07:02.130 --> 07:03.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:03.798 --> 07:05.091
<i>- Your initial weld</i>
<i>on this billet</i>

07:05.091 --> 07:06.635
<i>is the most critical part.</i>

07:06.635 --> 07:08.595
It fails,
you need to start over.

07:08.595 --> 07:10.013
And I've used all my metal,

07:10.013 --> 07:11.681
so it better not fail.

07:11.681 --> 07:14.476
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:14.476 --> 07:16.186
What the [bleep]?

07:16.186 --> 07:17.854
- Uh-oh. Uh-oh.

07:17.854 --> 07:18.938
- Trouble with big blue.
- That's not good.

07:18.938 --> 07:21.191
- Big blue don't work.

07:21.191 --> 07:22.942
- It looks like big blue
is down for the count.

07:22.942 --> 07:24.069
- No way.

07:24.069 --> 07:25.570
- [bleep], [bleep], [bleep].

07:25.570 --> 07:26.988
<i>Tools do break.</i>

07:26.988 --> 07:28.782
It's just, this is
the worst time

07:28.782 --> 07:29.949
<i>for a tool to break.</i>

07:29.949 --> 07:31.201
[bleep].

07:31.201 --> 07:33.703
- Nick is pissed.
- [bleep].

07:33.703 --> 07:35.163
<i>I'm not gonna let this</i>
<i>slow me down.</i>

07:35.163 --> 07:36.748
I'm not gonna let big blue

07:36.748 --> 07:38.667
take my $50,000
out of my pocket.

07:38.667 --> 07:40.001
I'm gonna take out
my frustration

07:40.001 --> 07:41.711
and set that billet by hand.

07:41.711 --> 07:43.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:43.171 --> 07:44.798
- Yeah, hit it!
- Look at him go!

07:44.798 --> 07:46.299
Nail it, baby!

07:46.299 --> 07:48.051
- Champion mentality!

07:48.051 --> 07:49.761
- [grunting]
[metal clanging]

07:49.761 --> 07:51.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:51.346 --> 07:52.931
- Suddenly, the power hammer
decides

07:52.931 --> 07:54.516
that it doesn't want to
function any longer.

07:54.516 --> 07:56.726
- To have that hammer down

07:56.726 --> 07:58.395
in the middle
of a competition like this,

07:58.395 --> 08:00.980
where these stacks
are so tall--

08:00.980 --> 08:02.816
they are so intense--

08:02.816 --> 08:05.860
it really puts a damper
in our competitors' day.

08:05.860 --> 08:07.821
But these guys are champions.

08:07.821 --> 08:10.699
They know how to overcome
unforeseen challenges.

08:10.699 --> 08:11.908
- Is that a yes
on the power hammer?

08:11.908 --> 08:12.909
Yes, yes, yes?

08:12.909 --> 08:14.661
- Yeah!

08:14.661 --> 08:16.329
- And the blue's back!
- Big blue is working.

08:16.329 --> 08:18.039
- Thank you so much.

08:18.039 --> 08:19.541
- Praise the Lord.

08:19.541 --> 08:20.834
- Bladesmiths!

08:20.834 --> 08:22.919
You have just 90 minutes
remaining

08:22.919 --> 08:23.962
to finish your work!

08:23.962 --> 08:25.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:25.630 --> 08:27.382
<i>- The two billets weld</i>
<i>really well.</i>

08:27.382 --> 08:29.300
But they're pretty burned

08:29.300 --> 08:31.386
from having forged them
out several heats

08:31.386 --> 08:32.762
<i>with lots of flux on there.</i>

08:32.762 --> 08:34.848
And I have to get it all off.

08:34.848 --> 08:36.808
<i>If you don't get</i>
<i>the old, dead, dry flux</i>

08:36.808 --> 08:37.892
<i>that's on there,</i>

08:37.892 --> 08:39.644
your steel's not gonna weld.

08:39.644 --> 08:41.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:41.271 --> 08:43.231
- Kirk is putting a
lot of investment

08:43.231 --> 08:44.691
into this stacking.

08:44.691 --> 08:46.484
He has to clean
his billet all up--

08:46.484 --> 08:47.694
both billets he has to clean.

08:47.694 --> 08:49.070
It's a time investment.

08:49.070 --> 08:50.655
- Now that
I'm thinking about it,

08:50.655 --> 08:51.614
it may have not been
the fastest

08:51.614 --> 08:53.408
or the greatest plan.

08:53.408 --> 08:54.868
<i>But I have to work my plan</i>

08:54.868 --> 08:56.202
because I'm into it
the whole way.

08:56.202 --> 08:58.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:58.496 --> 09:00.498
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:00.498 --> 09:02.959
<i>- It may look like I'm taking</i>
<i>a extra-long time.</i>

09:02.959 --> 09:04.753
I'm basically the last one

09:04.753 --> 09:06.713
<i>to get my weld going.</i>

09:06.713 --> 09:10.216
However, slow is smooth.
Smooth is fast.

09:10.216 --> 09:12.135
My biggest concern right now

09:12.135 --> 09:14.012
is a clean weld
and a tight weld.

09:14.012 --> 09:15.597
That's all I can think about
at this moment.

09:15.597 --> 09:17.807
<i>Nothing else matters.</i>

09:17.807 --> 09:19.809
<i>I find the biggest hammer</i>
<i>I can find.</i>

09:19.809 --> 09:20.935
<i>A few strikes,</i>

09:20.935 --> 09:22.187
<i>re-flux,</i>

09:22.187 --> 09:23.521
<i>back in the fire.</i>

09:23.521 --> 09:24.814
<i>And I did it three times</i>

09:24.814 --> 09:26.357
<i>just to make sure.</i>

09:26.357 --> 09:27.859
Once the weld is set,

09:27.859 --> 09:28.818
then I feel confident...

09:28.818 --> 09:30.361
Hot steel!

09:30.361 --> 09:32.697
<i>That I can go to</i>
<i>the power hammer.</i>

09:32.697 --> 09:34.574
<i>It is a solid billet</i>
<i>all the way through.</i>

09:34.574 --> 09:36.493
It is perfect.

09:36.493 --> 09:37.744
Hot steel.

09:37.744 --> 09:39.287
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:39.287 --> 09:40.789
- Derick's billet is tiny.

09:40.789 --> 09:42.290
I mean, it's not even
an inch wide.

09:42.290 --> 09:44.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:44.709 --> 09:48.379
- I am still not where I
want to be time-wise.

09:48.379 --> 09:50.256
<i>But the power hammer working</i>

09:50.256 --> 09:51.382
<i>has definitely made this</i>

09:51.382 --> 09:53.843
<i>a little more feasible.</i>

09:53.843 --> 09:56.554
<i>- The two pieces are sticking</i>
<i>just fine.</i>

09:56.554 --> 09:58.431
Now I can actually start
drawing this thing out

09:58.431 --> 10:00.600
<i>and working on my profile.</i>

10:00.600 --> 10:01.810
<i>And the thing that</i>
<i>is important</i>

10:01.810 --> 10:03.978
is the curve to the wakizashi.

10:03.978 --> 10:05.772
<i>And curves are what I do.</i>

10:05.772 --> 10:08.608
- With Kirk, you just see
that farrier's technique.

10:08.608 --> 10:09.943
He whips that hammer

10:09.943 --> 10:11.444
and he kind of hinges

10:11.444 --> 10:13.905
at the hips at the same time.
- Yep.

10:13.905 --> 10:16.533
<i>- I take my habaki sample,</i>
<i>and on the blade, I mark</i>

10:16.533 --> 10:18.076
<i>the points at which</i>
<i>it needs to be</i>

10:18.076 --> 10:19.744
so I don't go too far
in the grinder.

10:19.744 --> 10:23.706
- That habaki
is so specific in size.

10:23.706 --> 10:25.708
- Normally, you would
make the blade

10:25.708 --> 10:28.211
and then set the habaki
to the blade.

10:28.211 --> 10:30.755
The habaki is actually
to keep the blade

10:30.755 --> 10:33.091
locked into its scabbard--
primarily.

10:33.091 --> 10:36.386
<i>It also keeps</i>
<i>the guard from sliding up.</i>

10:36.386 --> 10:38.429
It's gonna be very important
to how this thing works out.

10:38.429 --> 10:39.597
[machine grinding]

10:39.597 --> 10:41.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:41.015 --> 10:44.144
- Dave over at the hero weapon

10:44.144 --> 10:46.479
just matching everything up.

10:46.479 --> 10:47.772
<i>- Having the blade there</i>

10:47.772 --> 10:49.190
<i>as a reference,</i>

10:49.190 --> 10:51.317
it's like having
an open-book test.

10:51.317 --> 10:53.278
<i>I'm taking the measurements</i>
<i>off of it.</i>

10:53.278 --> 10:55.488
I can see the curve
of the blade.

10:55.488 --> 10:58.199
I can see where
the handle begins.

10:58.199 --> 11:01.327
<i>There's so much</i>
<i>that's presented to you.</i>

11:01.327 --> 11:03.621
I'd be a fool not
to take advantage of that.

11:03.621 --> 11:05.165
- Dave's billet is just looking

11:05.165 --> 11:07.625
exactly the right shape
and size.

11:07.625 --> 11:09.252
- You have 45 minutes remaining

11:09.252 --> 11:11.045
to finish your work.

11:11.045 --> 11:13.173
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:13.173 --> 11:14.424
<i>[dramatic musical flair]</i>

11:14.424 --> 11:15.925
Kirk is in the quench.
- Oh.

11:15.925 --> 11:17.635
- He's stirring it around.

11:17.635 --> 11:20.638
- That's a good recipe
for bending.

11:20.638 --> 11:23.224
And not surprisingly,
there's a warp.

11:23.224 --> 11:25.476
- I need to get this bend out.

11:25.476 --> 11:28.104
<i>I press it down onto</i>
<i>the cold surface of the anvil</i>

11:28.104 --> 11:29.772
so it'll suck the heat
out of it

11:29.772 --> 11:31.316
and contract that side

11:31.316 --> 11:33.151
<i>and pull that bend straight.</i>

11:33.151 --> 11:35.069
And by golly, it worked.

11:35.069 --> 11:36.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:36.571 --> 11:39.073
- Derick has quenched
his blade.

11:39.073 --> 11:41.409
<i>- I'm really happy</i>
<i>with the harden, but, uh,</i>

11:41.409 --> 11:42.577
it's so curved.

11:42.577 --> 11:43.953
<i>[intense music]</i>

11:43.953 --> 11:46.247
<i>That is "Bad News Bears."</i>

11:46.247 --> 11:48.374
<i>But this little voice</i>
<i>in my head goes,</i>

11:48.374 --> 11:49.959
"You could probably just
put in on your thigh

11:49.959 --> 11:51.669
"and just give it a--
just a little bit of...

11:51.669 --> 11:52.962
<i>just a little bit."</i>

11:52.962 --> 11:55.006
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:55.006 --> 11:56.049
Agh!

11:56.049 --> 11:57.258
- Oh, no.

11:57.258 --> 11:58.760
- What just...

11:58.760 --> 12:00.261
- Oh, my God!
- He broke the blade.

12:00.261 --> 12:02.513
- No, no. [bleep].
- With 30 minutes to go.

12:02.513 --> 12:05.725
<i>- I swear I put less than</i>
<i>two pounds of force on it,</i>

12:05.725 --> 12:07.352
<i>and I just sheared</i>
<i>that thing in half.</i>

12:07.352 --> 12:08.811
- Oh, wow.

12:08.811 --> 12:10.521
<i>- Holy [bleep].</i>

12:10.521 --> 12:12.607
<i>My day just got wrecked.</i>

12:12.607 --> 12:15.777
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:15.777 --> 12:17.570
- So with 30 minutes
left on the clock,

12:17.570 --> 12:18.863
Derick's blade is broken.

12:18.863 --> 12:20.281
<i>- It's just gone.</i>

12:20.281 --> 12:21.950
I'm not sure I'm gonna
get this done.

12:21.950 --> 12:24.160
<i>But then I'm like, "All right,</i>

12:24.160 --> 12:25.245
"I've got another section
of billet.

12:25.245 --> 12:26.996
Let's forge this sucker out."

12:26.996 --> 12:29.916
- Derick, back in the forge.
- Come on.

12:29.916 --> 12:32.752
- I feel like if he really
put his mind to it,

12:32.752 --> 12:34.337
Derick could make this happen.

12:34.337 --> 12:35.922
- Yeah, I believe it.

12:35.922 --> 12:38.049
<i>- But I was weighing it</i>
<i>in my head,</i>

12:38.049 --> 12:39.467
<i>and I decided</i>

12:39.467 --> 12:40.635
I don't have the time
to do that.

12:40.635 --> 12:42.679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:42.679 --> 12:44.639
- Well, that's great.

12:44.639 --> 12:46.349
<i>Either I MIG-weld</i>
<i>this thing together,</i>

12:46.349 --> 12:48.309
or I don't have something
to turn in.

12:48.309 --> 12:50.687
- He's butted
the two ends together

12:50.687 --> 12:52.814
and he's welding the blade
back together

12:52.814 --> 12:54.274
rather than reforging.

12:54.274 --> 12:56.192
It's gonna be
an inherently weak spot

12:56.192 --> 12:57.568
in the blade, is that correct?

12:57.568 --> 12:58.778
- Absolutely.

12:58.778 --> 13:02.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:02.031 --> 13:03.950
- Nicholas has just quenched.

13:03.950 --> 13:05.535
- [bleep].

13:05.535 --> 13:07.537
It's got a warp.
I gotta get this out.

13:07.537 --> 13:09.122
[beep]
- Oh, wait.

13:09.122 --> 13:10.331
Now there's a mad scramble.

13:10.331 --> 13:13.376
- Don't break.
Don't break.

13:13.376 --> 13:14.711
- I'll say it with you,
brother.

13:14.711 --> 13:16.796
Don't break.
- When all else fails,

13:16.796 --> 13:18.006
talk to your metal.

13:18.006 --> 13:19.299
<i>- I think it listened to me.</i>

13:19.299 --> 13:20.675
I think it was okay.

13:20.675 --> 13:21.759
Whew.

13:21.759 --> 13:23.928
- Ten minutes!

13:23.928 --> 13:26.014
<i>- The difficulty in</i>
<i>combining these steels</i>

13:26.014 --> 13:28.391
<i>will be in the quench.</i>

13:28.391 --> 13:30.893
And this is where
poor welds can open up.

13:30.893 --> 13:33.396
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:33.396 --> 13:35.064
<i>I'm pulling the blade</i>
<i>out of the oil,</i>

13:35.064 --> 13:37.400
and I notice a little wobble.

13:37.400 --> 13:39.068
<i>Wobbles happen in</i>

13:39.068 --> 13:40.862
long, straight objects

13:40.862 --> 13:42.572
uh, when you heat them
all the time.

13:42.572 --> 13:43.990
<i>So you address it.</i>

13:43.990 --> 13:45.783
- Ten, nine,

13:45.783 --> 13:46.909
eight,

13:46.909 --> 13:48.077
seven,

13:48.077 --> 13:49.871
six, five,

13:49.871 --> 13:51.539
four, three,

13:51.539 --> 13:52.832
two,

13:52.832 --> 13:53.916
one.

13:53.916 --> 13:55.543
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

13:55.543 --> 13:56.961
Shut down your machines.

13:56.961 --> 13:59.922
This first round of competition
is over.

13:59.922 --> 14:01.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:01.841 --> 14:03.885
<i>- I'm not anywhere near happy</i>
<i>with my blade.</i>

14:03.885 --> 14:05.762
I MIG-welded a blade together.

14:05.762 --> 14:07.930
There's a giant concern
right there.

14:07.930 --> 14:09.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:09.640 --> 14:12.477
- Bladesmiths, here
in the first round,

14:12.477 --> 14:15.021
we upped the ante by asking you
to make a wakizashi.

14:15.021 --> 14:16.481
Now it's time for the judges

14:16.481 --> 14:18.232
to take a closer look
at your work.

14:18.232 --> 14:21.402
Kirk, please present your blade
to the judges.

14:21.402 --> 14:23.446
<i>[intense music]</i>

14:23.446 --> 14:24.781
<i>- I like the curvature</i>
<i>of this blade.</i>

14:24.781 --> 14:26.157
<i>It's very subtle.</i>

14:26.157 --> 14:28.117
The steel looks good.

14:28.117 --> 14:29.786
You know,
once that habaki goes on,

14:29.786 --> 14:31.496
those plunge grinds
are gonna have to go away.

14:31.496 --> 14:33.915
Traditionally there's
a very small shoulder,

14:33.915 --> 14:35.500
really only 1/8 of an inch

14:35.500 --> 14:37.627
as it drops down into the tang.

14:37.627 --> 14:39.212
But what I like is that

14:39.212 --> 14:40.630
you've got the material here
to do that.

14:40.630 --> 14:42.673
Good job.

14:42.673 --> 14:44.926
- Nicholas,
please present your blade.

14:44.926 --> 14:47.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:47.553 --> 14:49.472
<i>- You have a really nice</i>
<i>piece of steel here.</i>

14:49.472 --> 14:51.140
<i>The welds look really good.</i>

14:51.140 --> 14:52.975
There is a little kick
to your tang in here.

14:52.975 --> 14:54.977
It just curves off to one side,
but that's a huge amount

14:54.977 --> 14:56.604
of tang for a wakizashi,

14:56.604 --> 14:59.816
so that shouldn't be
an issue to deal with.

14:59.816 --> 15:01.400
- All right.
Derick, please present

15:01.400 --> 15:02.944
your blade to the judges.

15:02.944 --> 15:04.612
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:04.612 --> 15:06.239
<i>- I like the fact</i>
<i>that it's got</i>

15:06.239 --> 15:08.074
<i>a traditional shape</i>
<i>to the tang here.</i>

15:08.074 --> 15:10.409
I would have liked to see
a little more curvature to it

15:10.409 --> 15:13.246
to make it be more
sort of a traditional shape.

15:13.246 --> 15:16.874
This is a very narrow blade,
um, and then there's the--

15:16.874 --> 15:18.626
the 800-pound gorilla
in the room.

15:18.626 --> 15:20.378
Uh, it did snap.

15:20.378 --> 15:22.213
You had 30 minutes left.

15:22.213 --> 15:24.841
I was thinking maybe
you were just gonna go for it

15:24.841 --> 15:26.592
and, you know, just blast out
a blade in 30 minutes.

15:26.592 --> 15:27.844
We've seen it done.

15:27.844 --> 15:29.053
But instead you chose

15:29.053 --> 15:31.013
to weld this one back together.

15:31.013 --> 15:33.099
That welding makes things
really brittle.

15:33.099 --> 15:34.767
- All right, Dave.

15:34.767 --> 15:37.270
You're representing
pirates everywhere.

15:37.270 --> 15:39.272
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:39.272 --> 15:40.565
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:40.565 --> 15:42.358
<i>- All right, Dave.</i>

15:42.358 --> 15:43.693
<i>Your design here is</i>
<i>a little bit more</i>

15:43.693 --> 15:46.028
on the extreme curve
than a wakizashi.

15:46.028 --> 15:47.738
More like--almost like
a saber-like.

15:47.738 --> 15:50.158
But to me,
a weapon's a weapon

15:50.158 --> 15:51.784
no matter where it's from.

15:51.784 --> 15:53.327
Don't tell me the Japanese
didn't have pirates.

15:53.327 --> 15:54.579
Good job, sir.

15:54.579 --> 15:55.830
- Thank you, sir.

15:55.830 --> 15:56.831
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:56.831 --> 15:58.791
- Bladesmiths,

15:58.791 --> 16:01.919
unfortunately there can only be
one tournament champion.

16:01.919 --> 16:05.089
That means that one of you
now has to leave The Forge.

16:05.089 --> 16:07.592
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

16:07.592 --> 16:11.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:11.220 --> 16:12.680
Derick.

16:12.680 --> 16:14.515
Your blade didn't make the cut.

16:14.515 --> 16:16.642
- Derick, you are definitely

16:16.642 --> 16:18.811
a "Forged in Fire" champion.

16:18.811 --> 16:20.188
But in this competition,

16:20.188 --> 16:21.939
when your knife broke,

16:21.939 --> 16:24.525
we just feel you chose
the wrong workaround.

16:24.525 --> 16:26.277
And with that weld
in the middle of a blade

16:26.277 --> 16:27.945
that's very, very lean,

16:27.945 --> 16:30.865
we just don't feel
it's going to test out.

16:30.865 --> 16:32.158
- At this time,
I have to ask you

16:32.158 --> 16:33.701
to please surrender your blade.

16:33.701 --> 16:35.286
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:35.286 --> 16:36.746
<i>- This was</i>
<i>the expected outcome</i>

16:36.746 --> 16:38.623
<i>of today's performance.</i>

16:38.623 --> 16:39.957
<i>We all make mistakes,</i>

16:39.957 --> 16:41.792
and this was a big one.

16:41.792 --> 16:43.461
<i>I recommend this experience.</i>

16:43.461 --> 16:45.546
<i>Yeah, if you're into being</i>

16:45.546 --> 16:48.507
a masochist, yeah, sure,
you should do this.

16:48.507 --> 16:51.219
<i>[laughing]</i>

16:51.219 --> 16:52.595
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.

16:52.595 --> 16:54.305
You've made it
to the second round,

16:54.305 --> 16:56.974
which brings you one step
closer to the title of

16:56.974 --> 16:59.810
tournament champion
and $50,000.

16:59.810 --> 17:01.520
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

17:01.520 --> 17:04.148
it's time to turn them
into functional wakizashis

17:04.148 --> 17:05.942
by attaching handles to them.

17:05.942 --> 17:07.610
<i>Your handles must include</i>

17:07.610 --> 17:10.154
<i>a habaki, a tsuba,</i>

17:10.154 --> 17:12.281
<i>and a tsuka handle.</i>

17:12.281 --> 17:14.408
You'll have three hours in
this round in which to address

17:14.408 --> 17:16.661
the flaws and issues
that were identified,

17:16.661 --> 17:18.412
as well as
assemble your handles.

17:18.412 --> 17:19.622
Good luck.

17:19.622 --> 17:21.791
Your three hours starts now.

17:21.791 --> 17:23.459
<i>[rock music]</i>

17:23.459 --> 17:25.461
All right, so three hours

17:25.461 --> 17:28.464
to fix the flaws that were
identified in their blades,

17:28.464 --> 17:32.677
get the habakis fitted up
to the base of the blade,

17:32.677 --> 17:35.012
get a tsuba-style
guard on there,

17:35.012 --> 17:36.806
and then a tsuka-style handle,

17:36.806 --> 17:38.599
which is a wrapped handle.
- An ito wrap, yeah.

17:38.599 --> 17:40.184
- An ito wrap.

17:40.184 --> 17:41.978
- So we're asking
semi-traditional,

17:41.978 --> 17:44.438
so they could use paracord
or they could use leather

17:44.438 --> 17:46.190
or they could use
the actual ito

17:46.190 --> 17:47.108
that's supplied over there.

17:47.108 --> 17:48.484
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:48.484 --> 17:50.528
<i>- There's a warp to my blade,</i>

17:50.528 --> 17:52.697
but I have enough thickness
I can grind it differentially

17:52.697 --> 17:54.657
and remove most of it.

17:54.657 --> 17:57.994
Then I have to do the fit
for the little...

17:57.994 --> 18:00.204
wasizaki or whatever it is.
[laughing]

18:00.204 --> 18:02.123
- Habaki?
- Yeah, habaki.

18:02.123 --> 18:03.749
<i>But I'm gonna be tight</i>
<i>for time.</i>

18:03.749 --> 18:05.543
<i>There's no question.</i>

18:05.543 --> 18:07.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:07.336 --> 18:09.714
<i>- So as an armorer,</i>
<i>I'm not really familiar</i>

18:09.714 --> 18:11.632
with Japanese swords.

18:11.632 --> 18:13.884
<i>And my knife does not</i>
<i>have the profile</i>

18:13.884 --> 18:15.595
<i>that a wakizashi should have.</i>

18:15.595 --> 18:17.430
It's gonna be very difficult
to finish this

18:17.430 --> 18:19.015
in the time allotted.

18:19.015 --> 18:20.933
Come on, sucker.

18:20.933 --> 18:22.351
<i>- Going to second round,</i>

18:22.351 --> 18:24.437
<i>my plan is one,</i>

18:24.437 --> 18:25.688
get the habaki fit

18:25.688 --> 18:27.523
<i>so it's tight, snug,</i>

18:27.523 --> 18:28.941
<i>it's not gonna move.</i>

18:28.941 --> 18:31.110
- When you're grinding
your blade,

18:31.110 --> 18:32.862
you need to grind
and check the fit,

18:32.862 --> 18:34.488
grind, check the fit,
grind--

18:34.488 --> 18:37.325
you want that habaki
to be tight.

18:37.325 --> 18:39.827
<i>- There is a degree</i>
<i>of precision that must be met.</i>

18:39.827 --> 18:41.287
<i>If you don't meet it,</i>

18:41.287 --> 18:42.872
blade's not gonna
go together properly.

18:42.872 --> 18:44.749
Things are gonna be loose.

18:44.749 --> 18:47.418
<i>And that will lead to failure.</i>

18:47.418 --> 18:48.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:48.836 --> 18:51.005
- How would you make
your tsuba, Dave?

18:51.005 --> 18:53.633
- You gotta figure
that the blade shape

18:53.633 --> 18:55.843
continues into the tang.

18:55.843 --> 18:57.303
It's gonna diminish
towards one end,

18:57.303 --> 18:59.055
towards the edge.

18:59.055 --> 19:00.848
So you really need
to get it fitted up well.

19:00.848 --> 19:03.434
- That'll fit in.
There we go.

19:03.434 --> 19:05.061
[flames whoosh]

19:05.061 --> 19:07.563
<i>- I have the habaki</i>
<i>on the blade,</i>

19:07.563 --> 19:09.565
and that gives me the position
and the shape

19:09.565 --> 19:10.941
for the tsuba.

19:10.941 --> 19:12.693
<i>I don't have a real good idea</i>

19:12.693 --> 19:15.112
<i>what the traditional shapes</i>
<i>and styles are,</i>

19:15.112 --> 19:16.447
<i>so I have a trick up</i>
<i>my sleeve,</i>

19:16.447 --> 19:18.449
I think, that will put my stamp

19:18.449 --> 19:20.493
of craftsmanship on it.

19:20.493 --> 19:21.827
- Oh, look at that!
- Oh, my God.

19:21.827 --> 19:23.079
- Oh, my God, that
is just awesome.

19:23.079 --> 19:24.580
- Look at what Kirk did.

19:24.580 --> 19:26.123
- Holy cow.
- Beautiful.

19:26.123 --> 19:28.626
- Kirk has put
a horseshoe design

19:28.626 --> 19:30.461
into his tsuba band.
- That is so cool.

19:30.461 --> 19:33.005
- This guy is a badass, man.
- [laughs]

19:33.005 --> 19:34.507
- I have to put
the farrier touch

19:34.507 --> 19:35.841
on everything I make.

19:35.841 --> 19:37.218
- Bladesmiths!

19:37.218 --> 19:39.804
You have just 90 minutes
remaining

19:39.804 --> 19:41.222
to finish your work.

19:41.222 --> 19:42.973
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:42.973 --> 19:44.934
<i>- The next thing is,</i>
<i>I grab my wood</i>

19:44.934 --> 19:46.602
<i>for the handle material.</i>

19:46.602 --> 19:48.688
- Look at Dave.
- That's what I like to see.

19:48.688 --> 19:50.648
- Dave's looking at the weapon.
- Dave right there, feeling it.

19:50.648 --> 19:52.066
- Yeah.
- It better end up

19:52.066 --> 19:54.068
feeling the same way
in his sword.

19:54.068 --> 19:56.987
<i>- The hero blade's handle is</i>
<i>quite a thin profile,</i>

19:56.987 --> 19:58.989
and I'm not comfortable

19:58.989 --> 20:01.367
taking my handle down
that thin.

20:01.367 --> 20:02.827
<i>You lose mass.</i>
<i>You lose strength.</i>

20:02.827 --> 20:04.662
<i>I don't want to chance that.</i>

20:04.662 --> 20:05.746
- Agh.

20:05.746 --> 20:06.997
- So when it comes to, like,

20:06.997 --> 20:09.625
the pressure being
put on these guys,

20:09.625 --> 20:11.085
would you say that Nicholas

20:11.085 --> 20:13.504
is maybe the most high-strung
of the smiths?

20:13.504 --> 20:15.047
- Oh, there's a frickin'--

20:15.047 --> 20:16.674
I am really, really worried.

20:16.674 --> 20:18.926
<i>I have 35 minutes</i>

20:18.926 --> 20:20.219
to get a handle on,

20:20.219 --> 20:23.931
pinned, glued, and wrapped.

20:23.931 --> 20:25.349
- Bladesmiths!

20:25.349 --> 20:28.060
You have just 20 minutes
remaining!

20:28.060 --> 20:30.563
<i>- My handle is set.</i>
<i>Time's getting short.</i>

20:30.563 --> 20:33.607
And now I prepare to do a wrap.

20:33.607 --> 20:35.568
- This is where having
a daughter

20:35.568 --> 20:36.694
might come in handy.

20:36.694 --> 20:38.612
[both laughing]

20:38.612 --> 20:40.197
<i>- I'm struggling with</i>
<i>the cord wrap</i>

20:40.197 --> 20:41.741
<i>only because</i>
<i>I've never done it.</i>

20:41.741 --> 20:43.284
I'm gonna get through it,

20:43.284 --> 20:45.119
<i>but I'm feeling</i>
<i>the pressure now.</i>

20:45.119 --> 20:47.747
I'm gonna run the [bleep] out.
[sighs]

20:47.747 --> 20:49.832
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:49.832 --> 20:51.667
- I'm buffing the blade out,

20:51.667 --> 20:53.669
<i>but I still have to finish</i>
<i>the handle,</i>

20:53.669 --> 20:55.337
put the pin in it,
and put the wrap on it.

20:55.337 --> 20:59.133
- This is gonna come right down
to the wire for Kirk.

20:59.133 --> 21:00.676
<i>- I'm trying to put</i>
<i>this flat braid</i>

21:00.676 --> 21:02.094
<i>through the hole,</i>

21:02.094 --> 21:03.971
<i>and it's fraying</i>
<i>and bunching up</i>

21:03.971 --> 21:05.765
<i>and it will not go through</i>
<i>the hole.</i>

21:05.765 --> 21:06.974
- Forget that hole.
- Abandon the hole.

21:06.974 --> 21:08.893
Abandon the hole.
- Start wrapping.

21:08.893 --> 21:11.145
<i>- It should be as simple</i>
<i>as tying your shoes,</i>

21:11.145 --> 21:12.855
but it's not.

21:12.855 --> 21:15.399
<i>Without a wrap I could get</i>
<i>eliminated.</i>

21:15.399 --> 21:17.109
- Come on, Kirk.
- Oh, man, you're killing me.

21:17.109 --> 21:19.236
- I got a cord
that doesn't want to go.

21:19.236 --> 21:21.155
- Oh, man, this is
a disaster for Kirk.

21:21.155 --> 21:25.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:25.117 --> 21:27.286
<i>- If I can't get this rope</i>
<i>through this hole,</i>

21:27.286 --> 21:29.288
I don't stand a snowball's
chance in hell

21:29.288 --> 21:31.791
of going on.

21:31.791 --> 21:33.125
- Oh, where is he going now?
- What's Kirk doing?

21:33.125 --> 21:34.084
<i>[intense music]</i>

21:34.084 --> 21:35.711
- Two minutes!

21:35.711 --> 21:37.379
<i>- So I run over</i>
<i>and grab the torch.</i>

21:37.379 --> 21:38.964
<i>I burn the end and roll it</i>
<i>in my fingers</i>

21:38.964 --> 21:40.674
into a point, and then
I stick it through.

21:40.674 --> 21:42.259
I should have thought
about that right away.

21:42.259 --> 21:43.469
- Good, he's in.

21:43.469 --> 21:44.929
- Okay.
- Don't worry

21:44.929 --> 21:46.555
about tying anything.
Just wrap.

21:46.555 --> 21:47.807
- He's in.
- Wrap, wrap, wrap.

21:47.807 --> 21:49.141
- Wrap!
- Come on.

21:49.141 --> 21:51.018
Come on, come on, come on.

21:51.018 --> 21:52.102
<i>- This is</i>
<i>the most stressful part</i>

21:52.102 --> 21:53.229
of the whole build.

21:53.229 --> 21:55.481
- Ten, nine,

21:55.481 --> 21:57.441
eight, seven,

21:57.441 --> 21:59.485
six, five,

21:59.485 --> 22:01.153
four, three,

22:01.153 --> 22:02.154
two,

22:02.154 --> 22:03.364
one.

22:03.364 --> 22:05.241
Bladesmiths,
drop your tools,

22:05.241 --> 22:06.408
shut down your machines.

22:06.408 --> 22:08.035
Stop what you're doing.

22:08.035 --> 22:10.412
This second round
of tournament competition

22:10.412 --> 22:11.872
is over.

22:11.872 --> 22:14.834
[all clapping]
- Whoo!

22:14.834 --> 22:16.627
[applause]

22:16.627 --> 22:18.754
- Man. [chuckling]

22:18.754 --> 22:20.798
Talk about coming
right down to it.

22:20.798 --> 22:22.675
<i>- I have a knot,</i>
<i>but it's only half of a knot.</i>

22:22.675 --> 22:24.677
And, uh, for $50,000,

22:24.677 --> 22:26.887
it all could come down to--

22:26.887 --> 22:30.140
<i>I may get eliminated because</i>
<i>I didn't finish tying a knot.</i>

22:30.140 --> 22:33.227
- Weaponsmiths, welcome
to the strength test.

22:33.227 --> 22:35.187
To test the strength and
durability of your edges

22:35.187 --> 22:36.856
as well as the overall
construction

22:36.856 --> 22:38.566
of your wakizashis,
I will be smashing them

22:38.566 --> 22:41.068
into this
Wing Chun bamboo dummy.

22:41.068 --> 22:42.444
Remember, this test
is all about

22:42.444 --> 22:44.029
what the dummy does
to your blades

22:44.029 --> 22:45.739
and not what the blades do
to the dummy.

22:45.739 --> 22:46.866
Kirk, you're up first.
Ready?

22:46.866 --> 22:49.076
- I'm ready.
Hack 'em up.

22:49.076 --> 22:50.286
<i>[intense music]</i>

22:50.286 --> 22:51.495
<i>Coming into testing,</i>

22:51.495 --> 22:53.789
<i>I don't think that the blade</i>

22:53.789 --> 22:55.165
<i>is going to be the issue</i>
<i>as much as</i>

22:55.165 --> 22:57.084
<i>that wrap not being tight.</i>

22:57.084 --> 23:00.254
So there might not be
a good enough grip.

23:00.254 --> 23:02.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:02.590 --> 23:05.426
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:05.426 --> 23:12.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:17.187 --> 23:19.690
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:19.690 --> 23:22.151
- Well, Kirk,
your edge held up really well.

23:22.151 --> 23:24.361
There's a tiniest little
edge roll,

23:24.361 --> 23:26.614
but hardly anything at all.

23:26.614 --> 23:28.532
The wrap, it's really loose.

23:28.532 --> 23:30.117
I can feel it moving around
in my hand.

23:30.117 --> 23:31.911
But overall, nice job.

23:31.911 --> 23:33.162
- Thank you.

23:33.162 --> 23:34.747
- Nicholas, you're up.
You ready?

23:34.747 --> 23:35.789
- I'm ready.

23:35.789 --> 23:37.082
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:37.082 --> 23:38.792
<i>Bamboo's tough.</i>

23:38.792 --> 23:40.461
<i>It's green bamboo.</i>
<i>It's even tougher.</i>

23:40.461 --> 23:42.004
I'm really a little concerned

23:42.004 --> 23:43.213
about what it's gonna do
to my edge.

23:43.213 --> 23:47.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.885 --> 23:50.846
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:50.846 --> 23:57.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:01.315 --> 24:02.900
- [chuckling]

24:02.900 --> 24:04.151
- Well, Nicholas,

24:04.151 --> 24:05.819
your edge held up really well.

24:05.819 --> 24:07.446
I like that you

24:07.446 --> 24:09.823
did a traditional-looking wrap
on your handle here.

24:09.823 --> 24:11.575
The wrap is tight.

24:11.575 --> 24:13.452
Your blade held up beautifully.
Well done.

24:13.452 --> 24:14.495
- Thank you.

24:14.495 --> 24:15.704
- Dave, you're up next.

24:15.704 --> 24:17.081
- Let's do it.
- All right.

24:17.081 --> 24:18.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:18.582 --> 24:20.250
<i>I feel really good</i>
<i>about my blade.</i>

24:20.250 --> 24:22.419
<i>There will not be</i>
<i>a catastrophic failure.</i>

24:22.419 --> 24:24.296
<i>I'm more concerned</i>
<i>about his ability</i>

24:24.296 --> 24:26.006
<i>to manipulate the blade</i>

24:26.006 --> 24:27.633
<i>with the handle I have on it.</i>

24:27.633 --> 24:29.468
I know it's beefy.

24:29.468 --> 24:32.429
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:32.429 --> 24:39.353
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:43.315 --> 24:45.526
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:45.526 --> 24:46.694
- Well, Dave,

24:46.694 --> 24:48.112
your blade's awesome.

24:48.112 --> 24:49.780
It's nice and sharp
all the way along.

24:49.780 --> 24:52.491
The bamboo didn't even faze it.

24:52.491 --> 24:54.201
The one thing that was
difficult for me

24:54.201 --> 24:55.202
is the handle.

24:55.202 --> 24:56.870
This thing is huge.

24:56.870 --> 24:57.871
- Yes, sir.

24:57.871 --> 24:59.498
- But, uh, all in all,

24:59.498 --> 25:00.541
well done.

25:00.541 --> 25:01.792
- Thank you, sir.

25:01.792 --> 25:03.127
- Up next is
the sharpness test,

25:03.127 --> 25:04.461
and for that,
I give you to Doug.

25:04.461 --> 25:07.089
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:07.089 --> 25:09.133
- All right, class-champion
weaponsmiths.

25:09.133 --> 25:10.884
This is the sharpness test.

25:10.884 --> 25:12.219
<i>[dramatic musical flair]</i>

25:12.219 --> 25:13.679
To find out how sharp
your blades are,

25:13.679 --> 25:14.972
I will take your wakizashis

25:14.972 --> 25:17.141
and slash away
at these pork loins.

25:17.141 --> 25:18.267
Kirk, are you ready?

25:18.267 --> 25:20.144
- Yep. Swing for the fences.

25:20.144 --> 25:23.188
- Let's do this.

25:23.188 --> 25:26.191
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:26.191 --> 25:33.115
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.616 --> 25:36.410
- Barbecue time.

25:36.410 --> 25:37.786
- All right, Kirk,
let's talk about

25:37.786 --> 25:39.204
your wakizashi right here.

25:39.204 --> 25:41.373
First up, your handle
construction.

25:41.373 --> 25:43.417
The laces are loose.

25:43.417 --> 25:45.252
That's an issue when you're
holding onto something.

25:45.252 --> 25:46.837
You don't want anything
loose in there.

25:46.837 --> 25:49.256
But your blade is razor-sharp,

25:49.256 --> 25:52.801
and overall, sir, it will cut.
- Thanks.

25:52.801 --> 25:54.386
- All right, Nicholas,
your turn. You ready?

25:54.386 --> 25:55.596
- I'm ready.
Let's do this.

25:55.596 --> 25:57.806
- Let's do this. [laughs]

25:57.806 --> 26:00.809
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:00.809 --> 26:07.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:07.941 --> 26:10.235
[metallic tang]

26:10.235 --> 26:11.945
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:11.945 --> 26:13.489
All right, Nicholas,

26:13.489 --> 26:15.407
let's talk about your wakizashi
right here.

26:15.407 --> 26:18.118
I love the feel

26:18.118 --> 26:20.537
and the balance of this blade.

26:20.537 --> 26:23.082
The handle construction:
it's comfortable.

26:23.082 --> 26:25.959
It's ovoid enough to where
it fits my hand nicely.

26:25.959 --> 26:29.213
And it will cut.

26:29.213 --> 26:30.255
- Thank you very much.

26:30.255 --> 26:31.423
- All right, Dave, your turn.

26:31.423 --> 26:32.716
You ready?
- Yes, sir, I am.

26:32.716 --> 26:34.259
- Let's do this.

26:34.259 --> 26:37.221
<i>[intense music]</i>

26:37.221 --> 26:44.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:49.441 --> 26:51.110
- [chuckles]

26:51.110 --> 26:52.653
- All right, Dave, let's talk
about your blade here.

26:52.653 --> 26:54.655
First up, the handle.

26:54.655 --> 26:57.074
- I know.
- [chuckling] You know.

26:57.074 --> 26:58.575
<i>It's a little bit</i>
<i>on the blocky side,</i>

26:58.575 --> 27:00.327
<i>but really, you have</i>
<i>that hot spots</i>

27:00.327 --> 27:01.745
<i>with those knots.</i>

27:01.745 --> 27:04.832
But most importantly,
it will cut.

27:04.832 --> 27:06.291
- Thank you, sir.

27:06.291 --> 27:07.292
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:07.292 --> 27:08.669
- Bladesmiths,

27:08.669 --> 27:10.754
the judges' deliberation
is complete.

27:10.754 --> 27:12.381
Only two of you may
move forward

27:12.381 --> 27:15.551
in this $50,000 tournament
of champions.

27:15.551 --> 27:17.594
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

27:17.594 --> 27:22.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:28.939 --> 27:30.107
Kirk.

27:30.107 --> 27:31.400
<i>[dramatic musical flair]</i>

27:31.400 --> 27:33.443
Your blade didn't make the cut.

27:33.443 --> 27:35.237
- Kirk, we really appreciate

27:35.237 --> 27:37.364
the art and the artistry
you brought to that piece.

27:37.364 --> 27:39.491
It's really creative
what you did.

27:39.491 --> 27:42.035
This came down
to the smallest of details:

27:42.035 --> 27:43.662
the unfinished nature
of your handle

27:43.662 --> 27:45.664
and the fact that yours
was the only blade

27:45.664 --> 27:47.457
that took any damage
in the tests.

27:47.457 --> 27:49.126
That's why
we're letting you go.

27:49.126 --> 27:50.794
- I understand.

27:50.794 --> 27:52.296
- Please surrender your blade.

27:52.296 --> 27:55.173
<i>[solemn music]</i>

27:55.173 --> 27:56.884
<i>- So there's a proverb</i>
<i>that goes around</i>

27:56.884 --> 27:58.302
<i>about horseshoeing.</i>

27:58.302 --> 28:00.846
"For want of a nail,
a shoe was lost,

28:00.846 --> 28:02.931
"and for want of a shoe,
a horse was lost.

28:02.931 --> 28:05.350
"And for want of a horse,
a rider was lost,

28:05.350 --> 28:08.270
<i>and for one of a rider,</i>
<i>a battle was lost."</i>

28:08.270 --> 28:11.690
And so, that knot--
not getting it tied

28:11.690 --> 28:13.275
and the handle
not being finished,

28:13.275 --> 28:15.569
that's my horseshoe nail
that was missing.

28:15.569 --> 28:17.404
<i>It just kind of culminated all</i>

28:17.404 --> 28:18.739
<i>in the loss</i>
<i>of this one battle.</i>

28:18.739 --> 28:22.993
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:22.993 --> 28:24.786
- Nick, Dave, congratulations.

28:24.786 --> 28:26.121
You've made it
to the final round

28:26.121 --> 28:27.748
of this tournament
of champions.

28:27.748 --> 28:30.417
And this is our final showdown.

28:30.417 --> 28:31.877
<i>- To win the tournament</i>
<i>of champions</i>

28:31.877 --> 28:33.337
<i>would be absolutely</i>
<i>life-changing.</i>

28:33.337 --> 28:36.798
$50,000 is not
a small amount of money.

28:36.798 --> 28:39.801
- We're sending you back to
your home forges for five days

28:39.801 --> 28:42.220
to re-create
a very difficult

28:42.220 --> 28:44.514
but iconic
weapon from history.

28:44.514 --> 28:46.350
That weapon is...

28:46.350 --> 28:49.102
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:49.102 --> 28:50.520
The nodachi.

28:50.520 --> 28:51.647
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:51.647 --> 28:53.065
- Ah.

28:53.065 --> 28:54.274
<i>- Dominating battlefields</i>

28:54.274 --> 28:56.318
<i>during the Age of the Samurai,</i>

28:56.318 --> 28:58.487
<i>the nodachi was the massive</i>
<i>two-handed field sword</i>

28:58.487 --> 29:00.447
<i>of the Japanese infantry.</i>

29:00.447 --> 29:02.866
<i>This immense weapon dwarfs</i>
<i>its cousin the katana</i>

29:02.866 --> 29:05.118
<i>by more than a foot,</i>
<i>with some blades measuring</i>

29:05.118 --> 29:07.162
<i>over 5 feet in length.</i>

29:07.162 --> 29:09.373
<i>The sword was so long it could</i>
<i>even disable a horse</i>

29:09.373 --> 29:11.500
<i>and dismount the rider</i>
<i>with a single blow,</i>

29:11.500 --> 29:14.419
<i>giving foot soldiers an edge</i>
<i>against cavalry.</i>

29:14.419 --> 29:16.588
<i>A testament to craftsmanship,</i>

29:16.588 --> 29:18.340
<i>the nodachi was</i>
<i>extremely difficult</i>

29:18.340 --> 29:20.592
<i>to properly forge and</i>
<i>uniformly heat-treat,</i>

29:20.592 --> 29:22.469
<i>so many were passed down</i>
<i>as heirlooms</i>

29:22.469 --> 29:25.138
<i>or used as offerings</i>
<i>at temples and shrines.</i>

29:25.138 --> 29:27.349
<i>Today, you can see the odachi</i>

29:27.349 --> 29:29.768
<i>in the hit mobile strategy</i>
<i>game "Dominations."</i>

29:29.768 --> 29:31.603
<i>Download it today</i>
<i>to participate</i>

29:31.603 --> 29:33.647
<i>in an exclusive</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" event.</i>

29:34.606 --> 29:35.941
The length of your blade

29:35.941 --> 29:37.776
from tip to the habaki

29:37.776 --> 29:39.903
<i>must be between 41 and 43</i>
<i>inches in length.</i>

29:39.903 --> 29:41.530
<i>You must include a tsuba guard</i>

29:41.530 --> 29:42.823
<i>and a wrapped handle</i>
<i>that is between</i>

29:42.823 --> 29:44.825
<i>20 and 22 inches in length.</i>

29:44.825 --> 29:46.576
<i>- I'm scared to death.</i>

29:46.576 --> 29:49.204
A nodachi is a gigantic
two-handed samurai sword.

29:49.204 --> 29:51.081
<i>I have never made a blade</i>
<i>this big.</i>

29:51.081 --> 29:52.874
<i>But I think I have</i>
<i>a little advantage</i>

29:52.874 --> 29:54.001
<i>as an armorer.</i>

29:54.001 --> 29:55.419
I'm used to making things,

29:55.419 --> 29:57.379
reproducing things
from history.

29:57.379 --> 29:58.755
- You'll have five days
at your home forge

29:58.755 --> 30:00.007
in which to complete
this challenge.

30:00.007 --> 30:01.508
At the end
of those five days,

30:01.508 --> 30:03.385
you'll return
and present your nodachis

30:03.385 --> 30:05.012
to our panel of expert judges.

30:05.012 --> 30:06.596
And after they've
thoroughly tested them

30:06.596 --> 30:07.848
and inspected your work,

30:07.848 --> 30:09.266
they'll declare one of you

30:09.266 --> 30:11.018
the "Forged in Fire"
tournament champion,

30:11.018 --> 30:13.270
who leaves here with
a check for 50 grand.

30:13.270 --> 30:14.938
<i>- I am one step away</i>

30:14.938 --> 30:18.025
from a purse of $50,000.

30:18.025 --> 30:19.693
And it's...

30:19.693 --> 30:22.112
it's kind of overwhelming
and awesome.

30:22.112 --> 30:23.363
- Good luck, bladesmiths.

30:23.363 --> 30:24.573
We'll see you in five days.

30:24.573 --> 30:26.867
<i>[music swells]</i>

30:26.867 --> 30:28.660
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:28.660 --> 30:30.203
- It's day one.
Uh, I feel really good.

30:30.203 --> 30:32.164
I'm back at my home forge.

30:32.164 --> 30:35.292
<i>I know lots about European</i>
<i>arms and armor,</i>

30:35.292 --> 30:37.210
but this is all
brand new to me.

30:37.210 --> 30:39.588
<i>I have a plan A and a plan B.</i>

30:39.588 --> 30:41.590
My plan A is
the Damascus billet.

30:41.590 --> 30:43.925
<i>My plan B is the 5160.</i>

30:43.925 --> 30:46.803
<i>If my Damascus billet</i>
